John Edward: Language is of great importance to the citizens of the world.
Independent schools in Scotland continue the tradition of excellence, which was reaffirmed in 2018 with outstanding exam results demonstrating individual and collective achievements in sport, art, music and other socially relevant disciplines.
These schools are part of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which has over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, and is committed to providing the highest level of service to pupils and their parents.
Independent schools seek to prepare their students for further higher education, their chosen career, and the status of world citizens.
As part of the education sector, which is responsible for the development and implementation of individual school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you are calling on his mind.
If you speak to him in his native language, you are reaching his heart.
This is a powerful example of how we cannot rely on English alone to build relationships and trust with citizens of other countries.
In the latest exam results this year, we see that languages are leading the league table and have the highest test scores in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received the highest grade of А.
Data from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of pupils achieved A in Mandarin (a dialect of Chinese), while 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners and 63 percent of Spanish learners also achieved A.
This is proof that in independent schools in Scotland foreign languages are undoubtedly considered vital for children and young people in the future.
Language subjects are now as much in demand as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other educational institutions.
A 2014 survey by the UK's Employment and Skills Commission found that among the reasons employers had difficulty filling job vacancies, 17 percent were due to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are thus increasingly becoming a key to a successful future career for young people.
Given that more promising jobs require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the profession a student chooses, learning a second language will have a real benefit in the future, since it will give him another additional skill that will be useful for the rest of his life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who knows several foreign languages a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to sustain a conversation, and French was the only language with a two-digit percentage  spoken by 15 percent of respondents.
That's why investing in language education is so important right now.
Knowing more than one language, especially in developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding good jobs.
There is a wide variation in the languages taught in schools in Scotland, with each school having its own set of languages.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered most important to the UK in light of the country's future development until 2020  such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, independent schools will always have a choice of languages with a teaching staff that is specialised in those languages.
Independent schools in Scotland strive to create a learning environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what future they face.
It is now undeniable that in the global business environment, languages are still vital to the future development of a country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages really need to be considered as "skills of international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, providing diversity and benefits for Scotland's youth.
It must be done well.
John Edwards, Director of the Independent Schools Council of Scotland
