North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions increase mistrust of the United States and that his country will not renounce its nuclear weapons unilaterally under any circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "substantial goodwill measures" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and committing not to build up nuclear weapons and develop nuclear technology.
"However, we are not seeing a symmetrical response from the US", he said.
"Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will not be able to unilaterally take the first steps toward disarmament".
While Ri repeated already-sounding North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, whereby North Korea would be rewarded for gradual steps, his statement seemed important in that it did not reject unilateral, unchecked denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent US president and the North Korean leader, which took place in Singapore on June 12; when Kim promised to start a move towards "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", and Trump promised North Korea security guarantees.
North Korea seeks to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also has resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
The US insists that denuclearization should be done first, and is increasing pressure through sanctions to force its goal and even object to declaring the war over, Ri says.
The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a utopian dream for people who don't know us.
But the real problem is that the continuing sanctions are increasing our distrust.
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister focused on three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in that took place over the past five months, adding: "If the side of this denuclearization issue was South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be in such a deadlock".
However, Ri's tone was markedly different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's missile launch on the US mainland was inevitable after President Trump called Kim a suicide bomber.
At the UN this year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still much to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump said he was not setting a time frame for the process: "Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter".
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should encourage Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The Security Council's sanctions must continue actively and imperatively until we see complete, final and confirmed denuclearization".
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006, seeking to block Pyongyang's funding of its nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly summit and announced after the meeting that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
