Harvard students learn to relax on special courses
A new course introduced this year at Harvard University has helped all elementary school students learn to sleep more and fight the chauvinist culture of constant caffeine consumption to stay awake all night.
One academic found that the most successful students in the world often have no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chesler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a clinical fellow at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
After his discovery, he was inspired to introduce the course by giving a preliminary talk on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of my talk, a girl came up to me and said, 'I wish I had known about this until I was almost finished.'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered to students for the first time this year, explores how a healthy sleep routine can help you achieve academic and athletic success, as well as improve your overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's Health Service, says the university decided to introduce the course after it was discovered that students were experiencing severe sleep deprivation during the school week.
The class lasts one hour, and students complete a series of interactive tasks.
One of the sections of the classroom offers a room in the dormitory where students, by pressing on coffee cups, curtains, exercise machines and books, receive information about how each of these activities and substances - coffee, light, which cause sleep deprivation - affect athletic performance, and about the importance of getting enough sleep every day.
In another section, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
The interactive campus map encourages students to reflect on their daily lives.
We understand that this class will not change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know, as any other person has a right to know, for example, how smoking affects their health", added Professor Chesler.
He said the false sense of pride in being able to "plow all night" is still quite common, and modern technology, as well as the increasing pressure on students, means that sleep deprivation is becoming a problem.
He says that getting enough good quality sleep is the student's "secret weapon" for dealing with stress, nervous exhaustion and anxiety, and even for dealing with overweight, because lack of sleep puts the brain into a hunger mode, causing it to feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chesler design the course by attending one of the classes last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to spread the word across the campus.
He hopes the next step is to ask all graduate students to take a similar curriculum before entering a competitive institution.
Professor Chessler recommends that students set alarm clocks to warn them of the time to go to bed and wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the blue light emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which disrupts the human biorhythm and leads to sleep problems.
