A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to see abnormal cells
A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to see abnormally growing cells and kill them.
Part of the vaccine's therapeutic effect is to teach the immune system to recognize abnormal cells
The method is to extract the patient 's immune cells and change them in the laboratory .
As a result of this change, the cells have the ability to see the type of protein that is characteristic of many cancers, and then the cells have to be re-entered.
The trial vaccine is showing promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
One patient who was given this vaccine, and whose immune system had learned to recognize abnormal cells, had had ovarian cancer in remission for over 18 months.
The method involves taking immune cells from the patient and modifying them in the laboratory, after which the modified cells can see the HER2 protein, which is characteristic of many types of cancer, and then the modified cells are re-introduced to the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, states: "Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine".
