The study, organised by the National Trust for Scotland, will study common toads, soprano toads, and the brown long-haired bat and Dobbanton night herons, which inhabit Inverewe Gardens, West Ross.
Special recorders will be installed at some points around the site to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys of the area using handheld detectors.
An expert sound analysis of all the recordings will determine the frequency of the cries, as well as the types of activities that the various groups of these animals are responsible for.
Then a habitat map is drawn up and a report prepared to create a detailed picture of their behavior on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at NTS, hopes that these results will reveal which habitats are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify major areas of habitat management, such as meadow formation, and ways to maintain forest areas in optimal conditions for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across Britain have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work, which affects their habitat and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting systems can pose dangers, as can fly tape, chemical processing of building materials, and cat hunting.
Bats are not really blind.
However, their nocturnal hunting habits are such that their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echo-location techniques to pinpoint obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 significant gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bat populations very seriously.
The organization employs ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, field inspections, and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up Scotland's first and only bat sanctuary at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
Property manager David Thompson says the estate is the perfect territory for them.
"Here in Threave, it's a great place for bats", he says.
